      <h2>Stop the WAR</h2>
      <img src="/images/2022/03/Rotary-in-Great-Britain-and-Ireland-supports-Ukraine-pdf-724x1024.jpg" alt="Rotary in Great Britain and Ireland supports Ukraine poster">

      <h2>Our Plan</h2>
      <h3>What is happening in Ukraine is a human tragedy</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>40% of funds go to food</li>
        <li>35% for Educational Funds</li>
        <li>29% for medical care</li>
      </ul>
      <p>We have a special relationship with our medical colleagues in Ukraine.</p>
      <p>On 10 January 2022, we chartered our first branch in Ukraine with 16 charter members. We were in discussion with them about joint projects and exchange visits and many other exciting opportunities for collaboration.</p>
      <p>The world changed on 24th February 2022 when Russia invaded Ukraine.</p>
      <p>At a meeting on 5 March 2022 attended by 80 people we decided to initiate medical aid for Ukraine.</p>
      <p>We’ve so far supplied £641,000 worth medical equipment to Ukraine – including 20,000 tourniquets, medications, VAC pumps and other life saving items</p>

      <img src="/images/2025/02/Ukraine-expense.jpg" alt="Breakdown of the Fellowship's expenditure on aid for Ukraine">

      <h2>Kangaroo Mother Care in Ukraine</h2>
      <p>KMC includes keeping small (preterm) babies skin-to-skin with their mother (or another family member), with exclusive breast or breast-milk feeding and medical assessment. Studies of KMC report increased survival, decreased infection, improved nutrition and growth and possible improved development.</p>
      <p>During active hostilities, the number of premature births increases, and the lack of electricity complicates the uninterrupted operation of equipment in neonatal wards. In addition, due to unpredictable bombings, it is necessary to immediately run to bomb shelters.</p>
      <p>In addition to the carriers themselves, a large part of the project is dedicated to training how to effectively implement Kangaroo Mother Care for healthcare professionals as well as parents of premature babies to ensure the most effective and efficient care.</p>
      <p>The carriers are manufactured in Moldova by Ascend Group SRL (Director Geta Rasciuc &ndash; sling and carrier expert with over 17 years of experience, board member of the International Council of Babywearing Consulting Schools), using local materials. They are manufactured in accordance with the EU safety standard EN 13209-1 using materials that meet the clinical hygiene requirements for washing at high temperatures.</p>
      <p>The Fellowship has supplied 8000 KMC carriers to neonatal units in Ukraine and have received excellent feedback from medical and nursing staff as well as mums and dads.</p>
      <img src="/images/2024/07/IMG-20240123-WA0017.jpg" alt="Mother holding her premature baby skin-to-skin in a Kangaroo Mother Care carrier">
      <p><a href="/kmc">More about Kangaroo Mother Care</a></p>

      <h2>Protecting pregnant women and newborns</h2>
      <p>The war poses both immediate and long-term risks to mothers, fathers and new-borns &ndash; among them premature births, which can lead to a host of complications both immediately and later in life. Colleagues from Ukraine told us of a high rate of Caesarean sections and a higher than normal number of children born with birth asphyxia (oxygen starvation). There were also several reports of direct attacks on health facilities and ambulances, and disruption to supply chains.</p>
      <p>Around May 2022, we became concerned about the impact of the war on pregnant women and the new-born, and prepared a programme to support 37 maternity departments. The Fellowship has so far supplied &pound;95,000 worth of vital maternity care medical equipment to these hospitals, to help pregnant women give birth in relative safety and with better care.</p>
      <p>It is estimated that these 37 hospitals will see about 30,000 births in the next 12 months. It is our hope that the vital supplies now available to these specialists will save lives.</p>
      <p><a href="/babies-of-war">More on the impact of the war on mothers and babies</a></p>

      <h2>Hats for Ukrainian Babies</h2>
      <p>Often considered an adornment, hats for new-born babies may be life-saving. Their heads are relatively larger than their bodies compared with older children and adults, and a large source of heat loss. Mild heat loss may be associated with poor feeding and growth; larger losses with decreased body temperature and an increased chance of death.</p>
      <p>The hats are often knitted &ndash; especially, but not exclusively, by grandmothers &ndash; sometimes along with booties and mittens. We have supplied 10,000 knitted hats and a large quantity of baby clothes to maternity units in Ukraine, thanks to the generosity of UK Rotarians and friends. (We are no longer able to collect or transport such items to Ukraine.)</p>
      <img src="/images/2023/01/2-Houston.jpg" alt="Knitted hats for Ukrainian babies collected for donation">
      <p><a href="/hub">More about Hats for Ukrainian Babies</a></p>

      <h2>Helping babies breathe &ndash; Neopuff</h2>
      <p>NEOPUFF is a simple device to help babies breathe; in many cases, having it in the right place at the right time makes the difference between life and death. In partnership with the Rotary Club of Klosterneuburg and with the support of RC Leoben, the Fellowship delivered 25 Neopuff devices to 15 cities in Ukraine.</p>
      <blockquote>
        <p>&lsquo;Such a device as Neopuff can literally save the future of Ukraine by saving newly born, little babies&hellip; you are a part of a big important project and we value it a lot!&rsquo; &mdash; Yuliya Bitner, Lviv</p>
      </blockquote>
      <img src="/images/2022/07/Rivne-765x1024.png" alt="Medical staff in Rivne, Ukraine, with a delivered Neopuff device">
      <p><a href="/helping-babies-ukraine">More about helping babies in Ukraine</a></p>

      <p>Many children have been killed or injured, many have lost parents and siblings, their homes, schools and playgrounds. We have been told that some have been kidnapped and trafficked. No child should ever have to bear that kind of suffering. They need mental and physical support urgently.</p>
      <p>Our support has been possible due the generosity of Rotarians and non-Rotarians to all of them we say – thank you.</p>
      <p><a href="/images/2022/03/Rotary-in-Great-Britain-and-Ireland-supports-Ukraine.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noopener">MORE INFORMATION</a></p>

      <p>The Fellowship was actively involved in relief efforts in Great Britain and Ireland</p>
      <p><a href="/helping-babies-ukraine">Helping babies live..</a></p>

      <blockquote>
        <p>‘It’s impossible for you to hear each “thank you” from the doctors but on behalf of them I can say that you are a part of big important project and we value it a lot!’</p>
      </blockquote>
      <p><a href="/our-journey">Our journey so far</a></p>

      <p>As an international group of healthcare professionals, we stand ready to help our colleagues in Ukraine to emerge from the current dark times into a bright future with a modern and compassionate health service.</p>

